Check out this great opportunity at Thurber House!

Thurber House’s Young Writers’ Studio is for 9th-12th grade students who like to write, want to stretch their skills, and hang out with other kids who also love writing. Their fall season runs Sept. 1-Nov. 24 online using Zoom every other Tuesday from 6:30-8:30 p.m. It is $15 per session and they have scholarships available to students seeking financial assistance. Get more information and register here: https://www.thurberhouse.org/young-writers-studio.

post_text:
Students and families should plan to attend the Virtual Back to School night to learn all the ins and outs of the upcoming school year including a school day walkthrough, Schoology information, Powerschool training, Counseling resources, Meet the Teachers, virtual schedule pickup, course supply lists, and more.

How to watch:

The Virtual Back to School Night will be streamed live on our Facebook and Youtube pages. It will also be recorded and posted on ACPA's website and shared through email shortly after the conclusion of the event.

Question and Answer Sessions:

The Virtual Back to School Night is designed so as to provide a significant amount of time for questions from students, parents, and guardians. This will be facilitated through the live stream on our Facebook page. To ask a question, simply type it in the comment box of the Facebook livestream. ACPA's administrators will be following the feed throughout the event to answer questions in real-time. Any questions that aren't able to be answered live will be responded to in the comment section of the livestream.

- Send an ACPA teacher an e-mail letting them know how much they mean to you!
- Pop in a teacher's office hours just to let them know how wonderful they are.
- Write a message on social media about your favorite teacher and tag ACPA.
- Engage in ACPA's Teacher Appreciation posts on social media (like this one!).
- If you have the means, visit our website to make a donation to the Teacher Appreciation Week Campaign.

This year more than ever, teachers have been called upon to completely change the way they operate in education and ACPA teachers have risen above the challenge, persevered, and continue to provide students the highest quality education possible. Let's show them as much love as we can during this Teacher Appreciation Week!

Here's what you can do:

- Send an ACPA teacher an e-mail letting them know how much they mean to you!

Last week Mr. Demland and Ms. Waluzak hosted a co-taught conversation with some AP U.S. History students called "Let's talk about Elvis." They discussed Elvis's complicated and nuanced legacy when it comes to music, race, power dynamics, and fame. Thank you to the students who were able to join us!

We're enjoying some of the ways that Digital Learning can break down some of the literals walls and time constraints we usually have to work around to make conversations like this happen.

Hello ACPA Community! We just sent out an email explaining everything you need to know in order to start this digital learning journey with us. If you didn't receive it, or know someone who didn't, please let us know! We will be emailing regularly and more frequently throughout these next weeks (Mr. Albeit will continue to be the primary contact person for middle school families), and it's so important that we are able to effectively communicate with all our students and families. You can also check our website for regular updates.

We certainly didn't expect to be here, but we're READY to be Trailblazers in this new period of education.

post_text:
Good afternoon ACPA community!

I hope you had a safe and productive weekend!

Eligible households can find information on applying for two months of free internet here: https://www.internetessentials.com

If you do not currently have a reliable internet source, we recommend that you start this process as soon as you are able to so you can be up and running next week. Let us know if you need to borrow a Chrome Book. We will release information on that process early next week. Many staff members are already planning some awesome things for online learning, starting next Wednesday! Spread the word and help each other get the resources they need. Stay safe, follow the CDC guidance, focus on your well-being and remember to practice our values throughout this crisis.

Mr. Gatto

post_text: We were proud to implement the first ever Cultural Awareness Day at ACPA Today. Let by teachers and student leaders, the goal of the day was to have courageous conversations, listen to and learn from each other in order to make ACPA a safe space for all members of our community, educate ourselves on our differences, and come together in our common and continual effort to work towards our value of Respect of Diversity.

What happens when 26 ACPA students spend 26 straight hours creating a performance centered on social commentary and self-discovery? Find out on Monday, January 20th, at 6:30pm at ACPA.

These students collaborated with local artists Caroline Bennett and Tripp Fontane throughout the entire creation process which began after school Friday and just concluded this Saturday evening. This one-of-a-kind show (free and open to the public) is a reflection of the process that each student experienced in creating their dance, poem, song, mural, video, and spoken word performance. If you looking for inspiration this MLK Day, this show is for you!

WINTERFEST IS TOMORROW at The Jo Ann Davidson Theater in Downtown Columbus. All tickets ($10 General Admission, $5 for children) will be sold at the box office beginning at 5:30pm. The Visual Art Gallery opens at 5:30, and doors to the theater open at 6:30.

WinterFest is ACPA’s premier art event that features the school’s most accomplished students in dance, vocal music, instrumental music, visual art, and theater. WinterFest is a life-changing event for our students, many of them have never exhibited their art on such a grand stage or for such a large audience. Winterfest is always a MUST SEE SHOW!

post_text:
Columbus Transportation did not run many of ACPA's morning routes today. ACPA Middle School has a digital learning day today and the district thought that to mean that the entire school was not in session. This is not the case.

The message we are getting currently is that they will not be running busses to school today. We encourage students to log in to Google Classroom if they are able to and complete any assignments that may be posted by your teacher.

We are continuing to do our best to work with Columbus transportation so that ACPA students are better served.

If you are able to get to school, we would love to see you. We are working as a staff to ensure that the students who were not able to attend today will have ample time to get caught up in their classes.

Please call the front office (614-986-9974) if your child is unable to make it to school today.

After some soul searching, Mr. Swedyk realized he liked math more and decided to pursue that path. Mr. Swedyk feels like he has found a home at ACPA mainly because of how influential the arts have been in his life. He was in every play in high school, thoroughly enjoys writing, and is a professional magician (something he wishes to share with and teach the students). Welcome to the team, Mr. Swedyk!

post_text: Welcome Theo Jackson (sounds like TAYO) to the ACPA community! He will be the middle school performing arts teacher, and the leader of our after school program. Theo has been making music around Columbus since...well, for a very long time! When making music, you will catch him playing piano, bass, drums, guitar, trumpet or singing - and often more than one instrument at a time! He has written 100+ original compositions for bands and theaters - and even one weird commercial you can still hear on the radio. Theo has a BA in Vocal Performance from Otterbein and is Guest Faculty at The Ohio State University teaching "The Singing Actor" class to develop young actors' ability to act through song. He has music directed over 30 musicals including our local Wagnalls Community Theater, CATCO and Actors Theatre, and The Ohio State University. Welcome to the team!
